><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uriliana.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Riliana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 22<br> <font color=#F4CC10>(4/5/02 6:25:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1073.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Was AA what you expected?  </span><hr size=1> The trouble with our Class skills as warriors is that they are mostly  offensive-minded, while the Archtype skills are predominantly defensive-minded (which is more in line with our class definition).  The offensive class skills do help with holding aggro some though.<br><br>My whole contention with AAXP is that while it gives level 60's something else to shoot for, all it entices them to do is grudge out eternally in the exp hunting grind.  I disagree that they had to do it this way (i.e. require that you hang around killing still more hordes of monsters to get your AAXP points).  How about scores of entertaining and engaging quests, only accessable to those of AAXP-levels, with AAXP points as rewards?  I mean it's only one idea, but the point is, there are other ways they could have done it besides "lets try to keep our level 60's interested by dangling some carrots and making them run a repetative monster crunching treadmill for all eternity to get them."  I think just giving high level characters new goals isn't going to be enough for Verant to keep people interested in the long run.  I think they also need to make obtaining those goals more engaging.  People need to be able to enjoy playing instead of just 'winning,' and I think they missed that mark with AAXP.<br><br>Riliana Steelthong<br> <p>You own being huge. You are the hugest guy around, without a doubt. Even really huge people whimper at your hugeness. And you are made of real